Climate Change and its effect on Maple Syrup Production in the US¶

Maple Syrup production has been a tradition for many American States since the 1500's. The first ever documentation of maple syrup production was done in 1557 by French explorer André Thévet (The History of Maple Syrup: From Early North American Days to the Present - Coombs Family Farms, n.d.). Since the 1800's there have been rapid advancements in farming and production techonologies, which lead to the US being one of the largest Maple Syrup producers in the world. The process of 'farming' maple syrup is a long time-sensitive and temperature-sensitive process. Here is a short overview of maple syrup production from the start:

  1. Spiles are inserted into trees and are left to collect the sap from inside the tree
  2. The collected sap is taken to a sugarhouse immediately through a vacuum pump
  3. Some water is removed from the sap through a reverse osmosis machine
  4. the remaining sap is then boiled to get rid of the rest of the water
  5. as the water evaporates, the sap will thicken
  6. when the syrup reaches 219 degrees it is ready to be put through production
  7. after filter and color testing it is ready to be packaged!

(From Tree to Table: How Maple Syrup Is Made | Publix Super Market | the Publix Checkout, n.d.)

click on the text that are underlined blue for images associated with the word

The production of Mapple syrup is confined to North America with the United States and Canada being the main competitors in the industry. the ideal season to collect sap from maple trees is either late winter or early spring. On average the period of collection lasts anywhere from 4-6 weeks (Maple Syrup, n.d.).

In order to have a manageable scope for this project, I am only focusing on maply syrup production in the United States. I used two datasets that were sources from Kaggle and the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration. Each Dataset will be introduced before the first graph is shown to organize the different data accordingly.

Now, lets look at the overall rate of production over the years when it comes to the United States.

In [70]:
overall_production = syrup.groupby('Year')['Production'].sum().reset_index()

# overall production lineplot
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 5))
years = overall_production['Year']
production = overall_production['Production']
plt.plot(years, production, marker='o', color='b')

plt.xlabel('Year')
plt.ylabel('Overall Production')
plt.title('Overall Production of Maple Syrup Over the Years')
plt.grid(True)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

you can see an interesting trend in the rate of production. In general the production of maple syrup has steadlily increased over the years since the year 2000. However, starting from 2017, the production has steadily declined. Today, Canada is the top producer of Maple Syrup.

So what?¶

It doesn't seem like a pressing issue, since it's just maple syrup. However, the issue of climate change is certainly a pressing issue. Maple syrup production is very temperature sensitive and no matter what technological advancements are introduced to speed the collection of the sap, the temperature and the environment can't be changed. Climate Change comes with many dangers and it can affect something as little as maple syrup production to the point where it becomes a larger part of the issue.

It can't be that bad...¶

No, its definitely bad. Climate change can drastically affect the amount of sugar in the sap, the length of time sap can be collected, and it can also encourage the proliferation of invasive species (Solin, n.d.). This is just the tip of the iceberg when it comes to maple syrup production. There are so many more affects that will take place and have been due to the increasing climate.

What can we we do help?¶

Having that mindset is the first step!

Becoming aware of the Climate Crisis and ways in which it affects all of us is something everyone should learn about

The internet can be your best and worst resource. Make sure articles are well credited when it comes to Climate research. In addition, incorporating small sustainability changes in your lifestyle can make a large impact on our collective future!

Counting Context¶

Both datasets that I got were from free websites. It is important to remember that historically Maple Syrup was collected by the indigenous people of American before colonizers arrived and took over. Now, the maple syrup industry has grown rapidly and many forget it's indigenous roots.

The second dataset from the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration is a government organization and has an extensive collection of data and covers a wide range of areas. Taking that into consideration and understanding the potential limitations and biases of that can also help understand the trends in the data.
